                <head>No. 284.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Walker</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>,</placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1888-04-28">
                            <hi rend="italic">April</hi> 28, 1888</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 78.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department has been informed by our
                    consul-general at Panama that citizens of the United States are required to pay
                    a capitation tax in that department from which British subjects are exempted by
                    virtue of the treaty between Great Britain and Colombia, of 1866.</p>
                <p>Reply was made to the consul-general’s protest by the secretary-general that the
                    matter has been referred to the supreme Government of the Republic.</p>
                <p>This Department holds that citizens of the United States in Colombia are exempted
                    from paying any tax from which the subjects or citizens of another power are
                    exempt both by the “favored nation” clause of our treaty of 1846 with Colombia,
                    and by the general principle of the law of nations which justifies this
                    Government in insisting that there shall be no undue discrimination against
                    citizens of the United States wherever they may be resident.</p>
                <pb facs="0557" n="423" xml:id="pg_423"/>
                <p>You are instructed to bring this question to the attention of the Colombian
                    Government, and to urge the Department’s views upon it.</p>
                <p>I am, sir, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">T. F. Bayard.</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
